Thinking back to work I did with back-propagation it seemed to be the 
convention in NN work to always distinguish between input, hidden and 
output nodes. Now, you can achieve the same results (e.g the LI you 
descibed) without connections going back to the input &#39;layer&#39; - you just 
perform the inhibition feedback in the first hidden layer. You can 
actually think of the input nodes as not actually being nodes, just 
connection points that the real nodes connect to to obtain input signals.

My own feelings on this are that it&#39;s far more natural to *not* 
distinguish between input, hidden and outputs nodes. This is how my 
current NN implementation is arranged. Each node holds a collection of  
Connection objects that point to the source of an input signal - that 
source can be another node or an element in an input signal array. By 
relying on a layer of hidden nodes to substitute for the fact that input 
nodes cannot receive connections I think we are effectively errecting an 
artifical barrier for the topology search process.

Ken, I&#39;d be interested in your thoughts on this one while I&#39;m still at 
the early stages of development.

Regards,

Colin
